    <teiHeader><fileDesc><titleStmt><title>The Ambassador in France (
                        Caffery
                    ) to the Acting Secretary of
                            State</title></titleStmt><sourceDesc><bibl type="frus-volume-id">frus1946v02</bibl><bibl type="frus-document-id">d67</bibl><bibl type="frus-document-number">67</bibl><bibl type="frus-div-subtype">historical-document</bibl></sourceDesc></fileDesc><profileDesc><settingDesc><setting><date notBefore="1946-04-25T03:00:00-05:00" notAfter="1946-04-25T03:00:00-05:00"/></setting></settingDesc></profileDesc></teiHeader><text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1946-04-25T03:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1946-04-25T03:00:00-05:00" n="67" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d67">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">851.00/4–2546: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Caffery</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1946-04-25T09:00:00+01:00">April 25, 1946—9 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 11:25 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1964. When I accompanied the Secretary to call on Bidault this afternoon,<note n="13" xml:id="d67fn13">April 24. The Secretary arrived in Paris on April
                        23.</note> most of the time was taken up with Bidault’s opposition to
                    trusteeship plans in connection with Tripolitania; against a Russian trusteeship
                    as well as against an international trusteeship. He repeated the arguments he
                    has advanced previously.</p>
                <pb facs="0125" n="107" xml:id="pg_107"/>
                <p>In conversation on matters in general, he was more vigorous in talking against
                    Russian pretensions than he has been for some time. When I questioned him on
                    this he said that in the Cabinet meeting today (my telegram 1962 April 24<note n="14" xml:id="d67fn14">Not printed.</note>) he had been given a “free hand”
                    in foreign affairs.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Caffery</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
